To understand the dependence of Rs,oc on ϕ, we first develop a general methodology to extract contact resistivity characteristic ρc(J), and then show that this is a property of the contact, applicable to both dark and illuminated conditions. The methodology is based on drift‒diffusion simulation of JV characteristics with bimolecular bulk recombination in the PAL between its two surface boundaries next to the contacts20,39, with optical transfer-matrix simulation of light absorption within the PAL when illuminated9,10. We imposed globally self-consistent boundary conditions, and assigned the residual “excess” resistivity to the total contact resistivity of the semiconductor/electrode interfaces. For dark JV characteristics, we computed the contact resistivity as: ρc(J)=V(J)-Vint(J)J\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rho _c(J) = \frac{{V(J) - V_{{\mathrm{int}}}(J)}}{J}$$\end{document}, where V is the applied bias, and Vint is the internal voltage across the PAL given by drift‒diffusion simulation. Thus this approach is advantageously model-free40–42; it does not presume the diode equation nor any particular charge injection (or extraction) model. The self-consistent boundary conditions were found by systematic search for global best fit to the entire set of JV characteristics (all ϕ) in the diffusion-current regime, where ρc can be neglected compared to bulk resistivity, subjected to the constraints that Nn is constant, but Pp ∼ (ϕ ‒ ϕpin), where Nn is the electron density at the boundary to the electron contact and Pp is the hole density at the boundary to the hole contact43. All other input parameters are known from previous work and assumed constant10,25 (see Supplementary Table 1).

Similarly, the illuminated JV characteristics in the power-generation quadrant, particularly for cells with sub-optimal HCLs, also cannot be fitted to any self-consistent {Nn, Pp} set with zero ρc(J) (Fig. 4d). In this case, Vint(J) is only slightly modified by the expected variation in Pp. So the marked dependence of Rs,oc on ϕ provides clear evidence for contact resistance. For illuminated JV characteristics, we computed this contact resistivity as: ρc(J)=Vint(J)-V(J)J\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rho _c(J) = \frac{{V_{{\mathrm{int}}}(J) - V(J)}}{J}$$\end{document}, where the order of terms is swapped due to the reverse direction of flow of the photocurrent. The illuminated ρc(J) characteristics thus obtained are shown in Fig. 4e. The close match between the dark and illuminated ρc at zero current ρc(0), together with their strong ϕ and J dependences, confirms that the excess resistivity is due to the contact resistivity at the semiconductor/electrode interface. This is not negligible until well beyond the threshold of FL pinning.

The FL drop at the contact caused by this ρc(J) creates a barrier to charge extraction by lowering the internal field (Fig. 4f), promoting non-geminate recombination in the bulk of the semiconductor and near-surface region of the contact. Figure 4g plots ρc(0) against ϕ. It reveals an inverse exponential-like dependence: ρc(0) ~ exp( − (ϕ − ϕpin)), decreasing from 100 Ω cm2 at ϕ = 4.7 eV to 1 Ω cm2 at ϕ = 5.2 eV, with d logρc∕Ωcm2dϕ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
