				\begin{document}$$\left( {\frac{{d\log \left( {\rho _c{\mathrm{/}}\Omega cm^2} \right)}}{{d\phi }}} \right)$$\end{document} slope of ca. 5 eV–1 in the vicinity of ϕpin.

To clarify the mechanistic origin of ρc(J), we first formulate a contact resistance theory in the current detailed balance formalism and then show that this leads to an intrinsic charge-transfer resistance that quantitatively agrees with ρc(J). Therefore ρc(J) is a fundamental feature of hopping charge injection/collection. The current detailed balance model of the contact is shown in Fig. 5a. Contact resistivity is modeled by site-to-site hopping between the two frontier monolayers (denoted i and j) across the contact. The net hole current density Jij from j to i under the influence of a small local bias ∂V, i.e., applied potential difference across the two monolayers of the contact (positive for forward bias), is given by detailed balance to be:Jij=e∫i,jαwijNi(εi)fi(εi)Nj(εj)(1-fj(εj))-wjiNj(εj)fj(εj)Ni(εi)(1-fi(εi))δ(εi-εj+e∂V)dε\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
